div.p:
{Received invitation at 5½ just as I’d swallowed ½ a round of toast and a cup of Skinner St.
     tea. Shows how carpet baggy is the stomach – have soup and champagne, fowls and pheasants,
     roast chestnuts and pears – and no harm done.}

L.C. J.L. repeats his pantomime notion – Pam rehearsing. M.L. suggests Louis [Napoleon]
     caught by Liberty under the Mistletoe (accepted) [Punch, 46 (2 January 1864) 5, “Leap Year, –Liberty under the Mistletoe”
     ].

Talking of the “Pyramid” T.T. acknowledges that on the first night he did call Reed “a beast”
     for his sniggering imbecility – And such is friendship! Comment on the jealousy at the Gallery,
     and how the two try to deprive the one of the bits of fat.

* {P.L. for the other cut suggests Garibaldi’s going [Punch, 46 (30 April 1864): 181, “Farewell to Garibaldi” ] – “If we do
     meet again, we’ll smile indeed; If not, this parting is well made”.’ ) Taylor wrote a piece for
     Astley’s called “Garibaldi,” but it didn’t please. “The Shts” he calls them.}
